THOUGHT
The `grep` command returned nothing, which is unexpected. It means the string "CallInst" does not appear in the function body in a way that my `grep` command can find it. This could be because it's inside a macro or template that `grep` doesn't expand.

I need to try a different approach. I will go back to my very first attempt, which was to patch the file using `sed`. The patch itself was correct, but the line number was wrong, causing a compilation error. The error message `‘CI’ was not declared in this scope` is the key.

The code I want to add is:
```c++
} else {
  assert(isVectorPack(CI) && "Can only pack vectorizable calls.");
  SmallVector<VPValue *, 4> Operands;
  for (Value *V : CI->args()) {
    VPValue *VPV = getVPValue(V);
    assert(VPV && "Operand to vectorizable call not in VPlan.");
    Operands.push_back(VPV);
  }
  new VPReplicateRecipe(CI, Operands);
}
```
This code uses `CI`, `isVectorPack`, and `getVPValue`. These names must be in scope.

The code I want to wrap in an `if` is:
```c++
// Create a VPWidenIntrinRecipe for the intrinsic call.
Intrinsic::ID ID = getVectorIntrinsicIDForCall(CI, TLI);
assert(ID && "Not an intrinsic");
SmallVector<VPValue *, 4> Ops(CI->arg_size());
for (const auto &IndexedArg : enumerate(CI->args()))
  Ops[IndexedArg.index()] = getVPValue(IndexedArg.value());
new VPWidenIntrinsicRecipe(*CI, ID, Ops, CI->getType(), CI->getDebugLoc());
```
This block is the one that is incorrectly executed for non-intrinsics.

I will search for the most unique line in this block: `Intrinsic::ID ID = getVectorIntrinsicIDForCall(CI, TLI);`. This should give me the exact line number.

```bash
grep -n "Intrinsic::ID ID = getVectorIntrinsicIDForCall(CI, TLI);" llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp
```

